 Sponsor Listing 



                    Property Spotlight: Class A Office Space | Clear Lake                




See All Bizspace Properties



 
 











 Enlarge





                Energy XXI USA Inc. is selling its Grand Isle Gathering System to CorEnergy for $245… more 








 



Energy XXI USA Inc. (Nasdaq: EXXI), a Bermuda-based offshore oil company with its main office in Houston, announced it’s selling a subsea pipeline in a deal that brings its liquidity to nearly $1 billion.
CorEnergy Infrastructure Trust Inc. (NYSE: CORR), a Missouri-based real estate investment trust that focuses on midstream and downstream assets, is purchasing the Grand Isle Gathering System for $245 million. The deal is expected to close June 30, according to the release.













 Enlarge






                            Energy XXI USA Inc. is selling its Grand Isle Gathering System to CorEnergy for $245… more 










 


Energy XXI will continue to operate the pipeline assets, including the Grand Isle terminal located on shore. Energy XXI will also retain any revenue generated by transporting third-party volumes, according to the release.




Cleveland-based KeyBanc Capital Markets Inc. served as the financial adviser to Energy XXI in the sale. Houston-based law firm Vinson & Elkins also advised Energy XXI in the sale agreement.
The Grand Isle Gathering System is 153 miles long and in the shallow waters of the Gulf of Mexico. In 2014, the pipeline transported enough oil to generate $486 million in annual revenue for Energy XXI, according to the company release. The pipeline transports represented around 42 percent of Energy XXI’s annual oil production for the fiscal year ending June 30, 2014.
Energy XXI also took part in a mammoth deal in 2014 that made it the largest public independent oil producer in the Gulf. It acquired Houston-based EPL Oil & Gas Inc. (NYSE: EPL), including its debt, in a deal valued at $2.3 billion.

Cara covers commercial real estate and construction for the Houston Business Journal. Follow her on Twitter for more.











 






